comment.shortText:
Creates a new Box object in memory, with all values initialized to NaN.
This is useful to hold the result of vectormath function calls in performance
critical workflows.
`boxClone` copies values from an existing IBox into a new box or memory location.

tags.text: copy the values from the given box into a new box

comment.text: destination box to copy values to

comment.shortText:
Determines wehre the specified point lies in respect to the given box. The returned
value is an OR of the possible values OUT_MIN_X, OUT_MAX_X, OUT_MIN_Y, and OUT_MAX_Y
indicating, for each side, whether the point lies beyond that edge.

Determines whether the second box is completely enclosed in the first. Each box is treated
as a closed area, so e.g. the two boxes may share an edge and this method would still return `true`.

Determines whether the box contains a given point. The box is treated as a closed area,
so points on the boundary of the box will still return `true`.

Grows the box to include a given point. If the point is already inside the box, this function
does nothing.

Computes the area intersection of the two box regions, as a box. If the two boxes do not intersect,
the returned value will be an empty box, i.e. with `maxX < minX` or `maxY < minY`.

Determines whether the two boxes intersect, as areas. Both boxes are treated as closed
regions, so e.g. this function will return `true` if the boxes share only a single edge.

Determines whether this box represents an empty area. A box is considered empty if
its `maxX < minX` or its `maxY < minY`.
Constuct a new box given `minX`, `minY`, `maxX`, and `maxY` bounding values.
Compute the smallest bounding box that contains both given boxes.
comment.text:
For example, if one box contains the other, this method returns the larger box.
If the two boxes don't intersect, this method returns a bounding region that covers both boxes.

comment.shortText:
Creates a new Intersection object in memory, with all values initialized to `false` and `NaN`.
This is useful to hold the result of vectormath function calls in performance
critical workflows.
Copies the values from the given intersection into a new intersection object.
Constuct a new intersection given `exists`, `x`, `y`, `t0`, and `t1` values.
Computes the result of adding the two given vectors.

Creates a new Vec object in memory, with all values initialized to NaN.
This is useful to hold the result of vectormath function calls in performance
critical workflows.
Copies the values from the given vector into a new vector.
Computes the straight-line (Euclidean) distance between the two vectors, interpreted as points in the plane.
Computes the squared straight-line (i.e. Euclidean) distance between the two vectors, interpreted as points in the plane.
Computes the dot product of the two vectors, i.e. `a.x * b.x + a.y * b.y`.
Computes the straight-line length (i.e. Euclidean norm) of the given vector.
Computes the squared straight-line length (i.e. square of the Euclidean norm) of the given vector.
Computes the Manhattan length of the given vector, i.e. `|x| + |y|`.
Performs a linear interpolation between the two vectors. The `r` parameter is allowed to be outside `[0, 1]`.

Computes the Manhattan distance between the two vectors, interpreted as points in the plane.
Equivalent to `|b.x - a.x| + |b.y - a.y|`.

Normalizes the vector to be length 1. If the given vector is the zero-vector, this method
returns `(NaN, NaN)`.
Returns the 2d origin vector, `(0, 0)`.

Computes the perp of the given vector, as defined by `vecPerp(a, b) = (-b, a)`.
This is equivalent to a counter-clockwise rotation in the standard plane.
Constuct a new vector given an `x` and `y` value.
Scales both coordinates of this vector by the given scalar.
Subrtacts vector `b` from vector `a`.
Multiplies the vector by the given affine matrix.
